<concept id="concept-8547" xml:lang="en-us" class="- topic/topic concept/concept "><title class="- topic/title ">The Basic Stitches</title><shortdesc class="- topic/shortdesc ">Learn which stitch to use for different repairs.</shortdesc><prolog class="- topic/prolog "><author translate="no" type="creator" class="- topic/author ">Sydney Lindain &lt;sglindain@ucdavis.edu&gt;</author><metadata class="- topic/metadata "><keywords class="- topic/keywords "/></metadata></prolog><conbody class="- topic/body  concept/conbody "><p class="- topic/p "><b class="+ topic/ph hi-d/b ">Ladder Stitch:</b><ul class="- topic/ul "><li class="- topic/li "><p class="- topic/p ">Moves in a simple up-and-down pattern. </p></li><li class="- topic/li "><p class="- topic/p ">It is useful for attaching patches and making temporary repairs.
</p></li></ul></p><p class="- topic/p "><b class="+ topic/ph hi-d/b ">Back Stitch:</b></p><ul class="- topic/ul "><li class="- topic/li "><p class="- topic/p ">Overlaps previous stitches, creating a stronger seam.</p></li><li class="- topic/li "><p class="- topic/p ">It is recommended for jeans, heavy fabrics, and long-lasting repairs.
</p></li><li class="- topic/li "><p class="- topic/p ">A stronger stitch where you go "one step back" before moving forward; best for heavy denim.</p></li></ul></conbody></concept>
